[2]
Date: Tue 10 Jan 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters Foundation AlertNet, Tue 10 Jan 2006 [edited]

More Than 70 Suspected Human Cases Undergoing Tests
----------------------------------------------------
Turkey reported another case of bird flu in a patient in the centre
of the country on Tuesday as the authorities sealed off parts of the
outskirts of major cities Ankara and Istanbul while they culled
poultry. 3 children have already died in eastern Turkey --- the first
reported deaths from avian influenza outside China and Southeast
Asia. Dozens of worried Turks have rushed to hospitals for tests for
the virus across the country of 72 million.
4 people were taken to hospital with suspected avian influenza in the
town of Aydin near the Aegean coast --- one of Turkey's most
important tourism centres --- fuelling fears the outbreak will harm
country's important tourist trade. Turkey has now confirmed 15
people with avian influenza infections since last week, most in
eastern, central and northern parts of the country. More than 70
people are suspected of having the bird flu virus and are undergoing
tests. Health experts say the outbreak in Turkey is the worst since
the outbreak in Hong Kong in 1997 when 18 people were infected and 6
died before it was brought under control. H5N1 avian influenza has
killed at least 76 people since it reemerged in late 2003.
Nancy Cox, an influenza expert at the U.S. Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention, said it was not clear why there should be
such a cluster of cases in Turkey. "We know that there is a
seasonality to influenza in birds and just as there a seasonality in
humans where the viruses circulate in the wintertime in the cooler
temperatures," said Cox. "We don't precisely know what the factors
are. It could be it has just taken some time for the virus to spread
within the poultry population in Turkey and for enough humans to be
in contact with sick and dying birds to be infected."
The latest victim confirmed with bird flu was from the central
province of Sivas, Anatolian news agency said on Tuesday. Parts of
the capital Ankara and the business hub Istanbul have been sealed
off for the culling of poultry. Inhabitants leaving the areas have
been disinfected.
The Turkish authorities said 12 of 23 people undergoing tests for
avian influenza in Istanbul had tested negative. There is concern the
deadly virus could hit a teeming city of 12 million which is the
country's commercial hub and gateway to Europe from Asia. Human cases
of the disease have been reported as far west as the Ankara area,
some 400 km (250 miles) from Istanbul.
Authorities have stepped up an information campaign on how to deal
with birds and called on locals to comply with culling regulations,
particularly in the poor mainly-Kurdish southeast. Critics say the
authorities are not being tough enough. Local authorities say the
best way to stop avian influenza is the wholesale culling of poultry
in in the affected areas, but they have struggled to convince
inhabitants in poor rural areas who make a living on raising their
animals at home. Authorities urged Turks to wash the hooves of cattle
and sheep who are often in close contact with poultry. Turkey is
celebrating the Muslim Eid al-Adha festival in which many people
sacrifice a sheep or sometimes cows.
Health Minister Recep Akdag said villages raising chickens for
killing or for their eggs was already a thing of the past. "Keeping
poultry at home and in coops must absolutely end," the Hurriyet
daily quoted Akdag as saying.
[By Paul de Bendern, Jon Hemming, Gareth Jones and Maggie Fox]
